commentBody:
@SP

My first college English teacher was who jarred me with a deflating grade.  

I think every writer (or, like me, who does it just for fun) needs someone along the way to point out that they're not already writing perfectly.  Not yet, anyway.

@SP
My 10th Grade English teacher gave me a D for a paper on Poe because it "read like a book" and he suspected plagiarism.
When I finally cooled off I was able to recognize the unintended compliment. I wrote every damn sentence of that thing.

@Francis

I can only imagine how exceedingly cool that last bit must have been.

Will probably confer crossword self-laceration immunity for at least a day or two, eh?

@Francis
Any video? Mind you, it will be higher, swifter, and bigger in your memory than in the quotidian truth. So, maybe better not.
Congratulations. Have a good bask.

@Francis

Go, Francis’s grandson! Woot woot!

Hold on to that good feeling. You deserve it. And I believe that every recommendation for your post is a recommendation for that boy. He deserves it, too. ⚾️ 😀

@fionatimes
Aha! Like soda vs soft drink vs pop vs (to my great perplexity) cola.  I grew up in 'soft drink' country and took me a long time to get used to 'soda'.
Other marker words include what you call the larger piece of furniture in the living room, and the shoes worn for athletic activities. All this before you even get to regional /accents/!

@SBK in TO
Not 'cola'. Never 'cola'.
Coke.

@Matt

How's life not in Maine? 

Anyhow, I'm not sure about brilliant, but I did think it was a pretty cute Tuesday. I know some would think it's silly too to describe a puzzle theme as cute, but I'm okay with that!  I mean, it's not Brad Pitt cute, but what are you going to do!?  ☺️

@HeathieJ

Turns out not Maine bears a striking resemblance to just outside Armageddon.  I'm thinking of maybe a summer home there.

MINNESOTACUTE seems apt here.

@Matt

You may not be impressed with the theme, but it’s a fairly standard type of early-week theme. 

Not every painting can be a Picasso.

@Matt

The columnists are paid to lean toward the positive side. 

If you want criticism in the other direction, perhaps a little too heavy, there’s always Rex Parker. He probably agrees with you.

@HeathieJ
Still got that JACKED angler in your head?!
It's been days...

@Ιασων

So you'd recommend Hemingway to someone who knows of him but is barely acquainted with his writing and is also old?

Cuz that's me.  I'm not sure how I'll react to his writing, knowing that his personality was the polar opposite of mine.

@Francis
Everything you've heard is true. Sparse. Spare. The man regarded an adjective as a trespass against nature and an adverb as a disease.
Think of him as the un-Henry James. Enjoy.

@Francis

Just read the story.  Don't worry about whether the Christ symbol is the fisherman or the fish.

There's a great arm wrestling scene.

@Francis
Hemingway's sparse style was "ground-breaking"--think of Dickens, who sometimes crafted sentences that were an entire paragraph.  Older novels went into detail describing surroundings, appearance, landscape, etc., and Ernest eschewed all of that.  If someone smiled, it was because you imagined it...  
Our jr year in HS it was American History and American Literature (which sometimes jibed) and we had to read TOMATS.  I never did "get" the symbolism aside from the crucifixion...  (We also had to read Thomas Wolfe's _Look Homeward, Angel_....and neither were really worthwhile for us as teens.  Eight years later, living in Germany, I found a copy and reread it....blown away by the story, the telling, the language, everything!  What a shame to be force-fed at too early an age!)

@Mean Old Lady

While it is true that 5/6 of Ireland isn’t British, the term “British Isles” is a geographical, not political, descriptor which does include both Great Britain and all of Ireland. The Republic of Ireland does object to the term, so it’s best to rephrase, but if it is being used, it does refer to both islands, along with some other minor ones. 

<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_Isles" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_Isles</a>

@Bob T.
Thank you for that. In which case you’re quite right; they are related to, but different from Langoustines.
I enjoyed my slap up meal today with abundant crustaceans, overlooking the bay they were fished from.

@lucky13
By the way, my favorite Hemingway book from my double Hemingway class at university is a work of non-fiction: “Death in the Afternoon” about bullfighting in Spain. Hemingway started off as a journalist. Also wrote poetry, short stories, etc. 

I did this puzzle without lookups except had to “check puzzle” for two little letters. I’m still not sure why the place for a golf pro is 8D LAST. I guess it has something to do with par. If the golf pro is Tiger Woods, he learned a lot from his dad!

@Ken S

Now that's funny. You would try to save their lives by helping them cross the street so they don't get crush. Or, you would take their lives by tossing them...alive...into boiling water. Ouch. 

Not a criticism...I do eat seafood, despite my ancestors' shuddering... but I just found that funny. I think in pictures and could imagine a cartoon panel around that.

@Nancy J.
Good for y'all!
We came across a CRAWDAD in the gutter when we were out for a walk...but it looked so odd!  Almost fuzzy!  When we got closer, we saw that the crawdad had her babies on its back.  Who knew?  Crawdad's are attentive parents!  (I admit we both assumed it was a female adult; the "nurturing father" is somewhat rare across the spectra of fauna...

@Nancy J.
"The mass movement of crayfish, often called "crawfish migration," typically occurs during the spring or periods of heavy rainfall. Thousands of crayfish may simultaneously leave their ponds or rivers to travel overland. This behavior is primarily triggered by drops in water oxygen levels, extreme water fluctuations, or searches for better breeding grounds."

<a href="https://www.youtube.com/shorts/882N1cXYAUw" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/shorts/882N1cXYAUw</a>

@SP

This was before my time but I am *so* sure he did.

No other reason for him to deny it parenthetically.

@Bob T.

Total props.

As for it being contagious...I'm not feeling it most days...

@Nancy

Isn't it such a relief to know there is something AI can't touch? Or...can it? 

Stay tuned...

@Mean Old Lady
The GOPHERS play the BADGERS every season for the Paul Bunyan Ax trophy. Minnesota are the current holders. So you were close.

@Josh
My sister got her PhD in Engineering, so she could teach and inspire STEM girls. (Most of her professors had been men.) But she also does triathlons, so maybe she's just a glutton for punishment?

@RiA
I remembered both those facts about you, and do not make light of them. My point is, that the text of the story never states, or even hints, that Nick is a combat veteran, and without knowing that, the story doesn't make sense. (I guess given the character's age, and the story's publication date, one might assume.)

You, in particular, are why I'm always careful to write "Northern Lower Michigan" in these comments.

@CQ
Just as with the Nick Adams stories, there's the subtext that the Teales' road trips were a way of coping with the loss of their son, in WWII--also through Nature.
The books are also a snapshot of America at a particular era--when there was a well-established infrastructure of roadways across the nation, but before the advent of interstates. We get there faster, lose so much.

@Grant
Our mom thought JELL-O was a vegetable, I believe.  A staple.  I have not made any in....lemme think....53 years, or possibly more.
And yet it's still in grocery stores.

@sandi
If I were to hazard a guess I'd say it's a flower which looks like a hand, a play on the column title which was drawn from the clue for 33D. 

Google Lens could not identify it.

@JW
GRE=Graduate Record Examinations--a standardized test one might take while applying to a graduate school. Proves you learned something in undergraduate college, maybe.

The Gopher is the mascot for the University of Minnesota. Gophers are particularly fierce animals. The equivalent for the University of Michigan is the Wolverine, which is much, much, fiercer. Ohio's is a Buckeye, but who's afraid of a tree nut?

